INTRODUCTION

Source code and corresponding prototype electronics hardware developed by THINK RADIO LIMITED, under contract to FINH LIMITED, for their client GIMI AB.

This source code, firmware and electronics hardware forms part of a product prototype consisting at its core of a user-configurable wifi connection,
thermal printer, user interaction buttons, audio output, RGB LED output, SD card reader, and rechargeable lithium-battery based power supply.

This application searches for pre-prepared thermal printer receipts on a designated internet server, then indicates by means of audio and LEDs that a new receipt is available,
and prints the receipt on the press of a user-button.

Everything is supplied on an 'as-is' basis, for the evaluation of a prototype product and no warranty is given.

BUILDING FROM SOURCE

This codebase has been set up for Platformio (on VS Code), but could be adapted to the Arduino IDE,
by renaming main.cpp to gim_pb.ino, creating a folder of that same name, and ensuring all *.cpp and *.h files reside in that folder,
and loading appropriate Arduino libraries, as necessary.

For instructions on setting up Platformio and VSCode see https://randomnerdtutorials.com/vs-code-platformio-ide-esp32-esp8266-arduino/

VIEWING DEBUG TRACING

Debug tracing should work on either Platformio or Arduino IDE.

OPERATION

1. On first-time power-up the device starts as a Wifi Server.

Connect to SSID ESP*** with your phone, open the browser, and enter the desired network ID (or use the button to select from a list of local SSID's) - and enter the password.

2. Once a successfull WiFi connection has been made, the device will reboot, and print the 'Welcome' receipt.

3. After completing printing the welcome receipt, the device will go into light-sleep for 60 seconds, then wake and connect to the server to check for new receipts.

If a new receipt is found, the device flashes the LED, and plays a sound.
If no new receipt is found, the device returns silently to sleep.

Every following minute, if no new receipt has yet been found, the device repeats this process.
If a new receipt has already been found, the device flashes the LED, but does not play a sound.

4. If the user presses the 'Ears' button, and a new rceipt has already been found on an earlier timer-wakeup - then that receipt is (freshly) downloaded and prinyed.
If no new receipt was pending, the deafult receipt is printed.

5. To clear the WiFi settings, hold down the BOOT button and press and release the user 'Ears' button.


HOW IT WORKS

The ESP32 is either running, or in light-sleep.

There are 2 event sources, the timer, or the 'ears' button (actually 2 buttons, wired in parallel).

Timer events are assumed to be much more frequent than button events.

Timer events only occur during light-sleep, and after a sleep of duration SLEEP_TIME_BETWEEN_FETCH.
On timer wake-up, a check is made whether any new Receipt has already been found on the server, on a previous timer event.

If no new Receipt has already been found, then a check is made on the server for any new Receipt.
If nothing new is found on the server, then this device returns silently to sleep.
If a new Receipt is found, then the appropriate LED's and sound sequence is played.

If a new Receipt has been found on a previous timer event, then only the appropriate LED colour is played (without the sound).

Button events may occur either when the device is in light-sleep, or whilst running through a timer event - but not through an already-running button event.
On a button event, either the new Receipt type found by an earlier timer event is downloaded and printed, or the deafult type is downloaded and printed.
This is always a fresh download at the time of printing, to avoid stale/out-of-date Receipts.
After the item is printed, the appropriate LED and sound sequence is played, and the device returns to light-sleep.

LIMITATIONS

This prototype is based on off-the-shelf hardware, that is not suitable for power-management.
In particular the printer will continue to consume significant power, even when the device is idle.
There is provision for an internal power-isolation switch, which should be used between product demonstrations.

There is no implementation of Open-Banking and it is envisaged that, due to the limitations of the ESP32,this would almost entirely be handled by Gimi's
iPhone/Android banking app.

HARDWARE

Hardware design starts out from an objective of a low-cost consumer product.

Core components:
1. Espressif ESP32 DevKitC WROVER                                 https://www.espressif.com/en/products/devkits/esp32-devkitc
2. QR-204 type thermal printer (with original enclosure removed). https://www.amazon.co.uk/YIWEOG-Embedded-Receipt-Interface-Printing/dp/B0DQT3PVHW
3. AdaFruit BFF combined audio DAC (MAX98357) and SD card holder. https://www.adafruit.com/product/5769
4. AdaFruit micro-speaker.                                        https://www.adafruit.com/product/3923
5. CREE X-ML Color RGBW LED on small aluminium PCB                https://www.cree-led.com/products/leds/xlamp/xm/
6. LX-2BUPS 9V high-current UPS and 2x 18650 Batteries            https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B0BQXMY42X
7. 2 micro-switches wired in pararllel.                           https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B07SPX492J
8. ESP32 Terminal Adapter                                         https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B0BCWBW4SR

1. This is a high quality development board, a production version would most likely use the Espressif ESP32-WROVER-E contained within teh development board.

2. QR-204 thermal printers appear to be a generic product available from muliple vebdors.
Whilst at very low volumes through Western suppliers the unit price is high, the volume discounts through sources such as AliBaba are very much more competitive.
Careful attention should be paid to the quality supplied.
Also signicant differences in print-qulity result from different paper-types - glossy paper producing the best grahpics-printing results.

3. This a convenient part for prototyping. In production the MAX98357 chip would be used, and either any generic CF card-holder and card (c.£1 at volume),
or it may be possible (if suitably sized) for audio clips to be stored inside the QSPI flash of the Espressif ESP32-WROVER-E.

4. Any similar micro-speaker of similar charceteristics will do.

5. This is an expensive high-power part, many cheaper alternatives exist. Note that a 5V power rail may be necessary.

6. Note that the power requirements of the QR-204 printer place significant demands on a battery-based. power supply.
Although rated at 5-9V, printing quality is both poor and slow below 7.5V, and a full 9V further improves performance.
The printer may draw up to 2A at switch-on, idles at about 25mA, and ramps to around 250mA during printing.

At a minimum, the battery/batteries should have a 1C rating/capacity in excess of 4000mAh, to accomodate a voltage booster.

7. Or any similar generic microswitches to suit the enclosure design.

8. In production this would be replaced with a custom power supply delivering 9V/5V/3.3V, and carrying the various other modules and chips.


